# The Base Case (Most Important)

Eventually the function reaches

```java
helper(nums,0,-1)
```

Question:

Is there any element?

No.

So return

```java
null;
```

That becomes

```text
1

/

null
```

which is exactly what a leaf node should have.

So the first line of `helper` is always:

```java
if (left > right)
    return null;
```

Read it as:

> "If there are no elements left in this part of the array, there is no node to create."

---

# Now look at the whole function

```java
TreeNode helper(int[] nums, int left, int right) {

    // No elements left
    if (left > right)
        return null;

    // Find middle
    int mid = (left + right) / 2;

    // Create root
    TreeNode root = new TreeNode(nums[mid]);

    // Build left subtree
    root.left = helper(nums, left, mid - 1);

    // Build right subtree
    root.right = helper(nums, mid + 1, right);

    // Return current root
    return root;
}
```

---

# Finally, LeetCode calls

```java
public TreeNode sortedArrayToBST(int[] nums) {

    return helper(nums, 0, nums.length - 1);

}
```

